{"title_page": "Takeshi Amemiya", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Takeshi Amemiya\n| native_name = \u96e8\u5bae \u5065\n| native_name_lang = jp\n| image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" prefix)-->\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1935|3|29}}\n| birth_place = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)-->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| nationality = [[Japan]]ese\n| fields = [[Economics]]\n| workplaces = [[Stanford University]]\n| alma_mater = [[Johns Hopkins University]]\n| doctoral_advisor = [[Carl Christ|Carl F. Christ]] <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| doctoral_students = [[James L. Powell]]<br>[[Victor Chernozhukov]]\n| known_for = \n| awards = \n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Takeshi Amemiya'''|\u96e8\u5bae \u5065|''Amemiya Takeshi''|extra=born 29 March 1935, in Tokyo, Japan}} is an [[economist]] specializing in [[econometrics]] and the [[economy of ancient Greece]].<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Roger |editor1-last=Backhouse |editor2-first=Roger |editor2-last=Middleton |chapter=Takeshi Amemiya b 1935 |title=Exemplary Economists: North America |volume=1 |location= |publisher=Edward Elgar |year=2000 |isbn=1-78254-311-2 |pages=311\u201322 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=SHnGSiiK4dUC&pg=PA311 }}</ref>\n\nAmemiya is the [[Edward Ames Edmonds]] Professor of Economics (emeritus) and a Professor of Classics at [[Stanford University]].   He is a Fellow of the [[Econometric Society]], the [[American Statistical Association]]<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Powell | first1 = J. L. | year = 2007 | title = The ET Interview: Takeshi Amemiya | url = http://journals.cambridge.org/production/action/cjoGetFulltext?fulltextid=578000 | journal = Econometric Theory | volume = 23 | issue = | pages = 155\u2013181 | doi = 10.1017/S0266466607070065 }}</ref> and the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] (1985).<ref name=AAAS>{{cite web|title=Book of Members, 1780-2010: Chapter A|url=http://www.amacad.org/publications/BookofMembers/ChapterA.pdf|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences|accessdate=17 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n*B.A., 1958, Social Science, [[International Christian University]], Tokyo, Japan\n*M.A., 1961, Economics, [[American University]], Washington, DC\n*Ph.D., 1964, Economics, [[Johns Hopkins University]], Baltimore, Maryland\n\n==Honors and awards==\n* U.S. Scientist Award, [[Alexander von Humboldt Foundation]], 1988\n* Fellowship, Japan Society for Promotion of Science, 1989\n* Fellowship, John Simon [[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation|Guggenheim Foundation]], 1975\u20131976\n* Ford Foundation Doctoral Dissertation Fellowship in Economics, Johns Hopkins University, 1963\u20131965\n\n==Publications==\n===Books===\n* {{cite book |last= Amemiya |first= Takeshi |date= 1985 |title= Advanced econometrics |location= [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] |publisher= [[Harvard University Press]] |isbn= 9780674005600 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/advancedeconomet00amem }}\n* {{cite book |last= Amemiya |first= Takeshi |date= 1994 |title= Studies in Econometric Theory: The Collected Essays of Takeshi Amemiya |series= Economists of the Twentieth Century |location= [[Aldershot, England]] |publisher= [[Edward Elgar Publishing|Edward Elgar Pub]] |isbn= 9781852787974 }}\n* {{cite book |last= Amemiya |first= Takeshi |date= 1994 |title= Introduction to Statistics and Econometrics |location= Cambridge, Massachusetts and [[London, England]] |publisher= Harvard University Press |isbn= 9780674462250 }}\n* {{cite book |last= Amemiya |first= Takeshi |date= 2007 |title= Economy and Economics of Ancient Greece |series= Routledge Explorations in Economic History |volume= 33 |location= London |publisher= [[Routledge]] |isbn= 9780415701549 }}\n\n===Chapter in book===\n* {{citation | last1 = Amemiya | first1 = Takeshi | 